The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Tandon prefers Chennai
                                                                                                                       7                                      Tandon prefers Chennai
            A STAFF REPORTER                      
	Calcutta: Ramit Tandon, winner of under-19 junior national squash title 2010, said that it was the level of the game in the city that forced him to shift base to Chennai.         
	Ramit, who was felicitated by the Calcutta Racket club, here on Saturday evening, said: Chennai is the hub of squash in India. There are more opportunities. The facilities are much more superior, and most importantly, one gets to play against competitive players there. In Calcutta, you only find club players, so the level of the game is not that high.Akhtar Ali was present as the chief guest and handed over a memento to the youngster.         
	It was the sixth national title for the 18-year-old city lad, who trains at Chennais Indian Squash Academy (ISA) and represents Tamil Nadu.         
	The class XII student gave the credit for his success to his parents and trainer Dileep Tripathy. It is tough, trying to pack in study hours, school, training But, I love the game and so the motivation. Thanks to my parents and trainer for helping me.         
	He draws his inspiration from the likes of world No.25 Saurav Ghosal and Egyptian Ramy Ashour.         
	The teenager who had also won under-11, under-13 and under-15 titles would begin his career as a senior next year.         
	Asked if the transition from junior to senior level will be difficult, Ramit said: I have played with some of Indias best and I think the transition for me would be smooth.                                                                                                                     
